3. Overall weighted average life expectancy

# overall weighted average life expectancy
total_pop = dat %>% 
  group_by(year) %>% 
  summarise(nc = n_distinct(country),
            tp = mean(pop)*nc) %>% 
  select(tp) 

avg_le_all = dat %>% 
  mutate(avg_life_exp = lifeExp * 
           (pop / rep(total_pop$tp, nlevels(country)))) %>% 
  group_by(year) %>% 
  summarise(average_life_expectancy = sum(avg_life_exp))

4. Life expectancy changing over time on different continents

## life expectancy changing over time on different continents

# a function based on previous section
avg_life = function(dat){
  total_pop = dat %>% 
  group_by(year) %>% 
  summarise(nc = n_distinct(country),
            tp = mean(pop)*nc) %>% 
  select(tp)
  
  avg_le = dat %>% 
  mutate(avg_life_exp = lifeExp * 
           (pop / rep(total_pop$tp,n_distinct(country)))) %>% 
  group_by(year) %>% 
  summarise(ale = sum(avg_life_exp))
  
  return(avg_le)
}

cons = levels(dat$continent)
avg_by_con = data.frame()
for(i in 1:length(cons)){
  temp = dat %>% 
    filter(continent == cons[i]) %>% 
    avg_life()
  temp = data.frame(year = temp$year,
                    avg_le = temp$ale,
                    continent = rep(cons[i], nrow(temp)))
  avg_by_con = rbind(avg_by_con,temp)
}

Print table using stargazer.

library("stargazer")
m_le = gapminder %>% 
  group_by(continent) %>% 
  summarize(mean_life_exp = mean(lifeExp))

wm_le = gapminder %>% 
  group_by(continent) %>% 
  summarize(weighted_mean_life_exp = weighted.mean(lifeExp,pop))

le = cbind(m_le, select(wm_le,weighted_mean_life_exp))
stargazer(le,type = "html",summary = F)

5. Something extra

From the plot in section 4, we can tell that the growth rate of life expectancy in Asia is the biggest, while Oceania has the smallest one. If, unrealistically, there is no upper limit for life expectancy, I would like to investigate at which year would Asia has the same life expectancy as Oceania, and what would be the life expectancy at that time.

To simplify the analysis, I assume the life expectancy would grow linearly, and the growth rate is constant.

# extract data for Asia and Oceania
asia = avg_by_con %>% 
  filter(continent == "Asia")
ocea = avg_by_con %>% 
  filter(continent == "Oceania")

ma = lm(avg_le~year, data = asia)
mo = lm(avg_le~year, data = ocea)
years = data.frame(year = seq(2010,2050,1))
asia_pred = predict.lm(ma,years)
ocea_pred = predict.lm(mo,years)

new_asia = data.frame(year = years$year,
                      avg_le = asia_pred,
                      continent = rep("Asia",length(asia_pred)))
new_asia = rbind(asia, new_asia)

new_ocea = data.frame(year = years$year,
                      avg_le = ocea_pred,
                      continent = rep("Oceania",length(ocea_pred)))
new_ocea = rbind(ocea,new_ocea)
new_dat = cbind(new_asia, select(new_ocea, c(avg_le,continent)))
